I'd like to create a template where when I create the page it allows for the same functionality re: linking as the WYSIWYG editor. So if I have a field titled issues, it allows me to hyperlink to a specific issues page that I enter. Right now it makes more sense for me to create a dummy page as a template and to copy and paste the contents of that page into new pages. Essentially the Template feature is useless for me right now.

h3. Summary

As per the attached screenshot, the page /admin/cachecontents.jsp is visually unusable.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Access the specific url: <confluence-url>/admin/cachecontents.jsp

h3. Expected Results
 * Page should load properly, like this:
 !result.png|thumbnail!

h3. Actual Results
 * Page is broken:
 !Screen Shot 2015-07-13 at 16.27.25.png|thumbnail!

h3. Workaround 1
 # Open {{<confluence-install>/confluence/admin/cachecontents.jsp}} in a text editor
 # Find the CSS in the {{<head></head>}} section
{code}
     .selection {
             position: absolute;
             top: 0;
              left: 10px;
              width: 380px;
              font-size: .9em;
          }
{code}
# Comment out {{position: absolute;}} with {{//}} CSS comments, like this
{code}
     .selection {
             // position: absolute;
             top: 0;
              left: 10px;
              width: 380px;
              font-size: .9em;
          }
{code}
# Save the page

h3. Workaround 2
 # Open the page on Chrome or other browser with a plugin similar to developer tools
 # Go to the broken page <confluence-url>/admin/cachecontents.jsp
 # Open the Developer Tools (Options > More Tools > Developer Tools)
 # Click on the icon to inspect an element: !InspectElement.png|thumbnail!
 # Hover the cursor to the part of the page using *div.selection* and click on it: !step1.png|thumbnail!
 # Make sure that the Developer Tools is on the *Elements* tab so that it will show the CSS and the HTML of the section you've just selected
 # On the Styles part in the developer tools you'll see this:
{code:java}
.selection {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 10px;
  width: 380px;
  font-size: .9em;
}
{code}

 # Uncheck the *position: absolute;* checkbox: !step2.png|thumbnail!
 # Close the Developer Tools.

This will break once you click on any of those links, since the CSS will be reloaded, but it helps understanding the options there.

